{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"736"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/736"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.55,0.13,0.27,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62551"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/736"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47998"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"3882"},{"type":"tags","id":"3884"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8143"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20009"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62551"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60 year-old woman is referred to a breast surgeon after the recent discovery of a 2.5 cm lesion on routine screening mammogram. Histopathological analysis of a core biopsy has confirmed a Grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, breast palpation confirms a hard irregular mass in the upper outer quadrant of the right breast. The axillary nodes on this side are not palpable. She is large breasted with a BMI of 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe surgeon plans for a wide local excision, sentinel node biopsy and adjuvant therapy based on the pathology results. A few days later, the surgery is carried out and the sentinel nodes are identified, with one node feeling enlarged and hard on palpation. The surgeon requests intra-operative assessment of the nodes, which demonstrates the presence of malignant cells in three of them.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wide local resection with axillary node sampling","Wide local resection and axillary node clearance","Simple mastectomy and axillary node clearance","Radical mastectomy and axillary node clearance","Wide local resection alone and axillary node sampling"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Ewide local resection and axillary node clearance\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a high-grade tumour that is reasonably small relative to her breast size. There is no clinical evidence of axillary node involvement prior to surgery. As such, a wide local resection and sentinel node biopsy is an appropriate pre-operative surgical management approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntra-operative assessment of the sentinel node is becoming increasingly uncommon, however a surgeon may be motivated to request it if the tumour is large, multifocal or if the sentinel node appears clinically suspicious (as is the case here). Sentinel node biopsy can help avoid unnecessary axillary lymph node clearance, which is associated with long-term complications and significant patient morbidity. The current recommendation is to spare the axillary nodes if the sentinel node biopsy demonstrates involvement of no greater than two nodes and the patient is planned to undergo adjuvant radiotherapy (as per the ACOSOG Z0011 trial). As this patient has malignant cells in three of her sentinel lymph nodes, the correct surgical approach is to proceed to axillary node clearance. \u003Cstrong\u003EWide local resection and axillary node sampling\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is inadequate when multiple sentinel nodes\u00a0are positive, as sampling alone may miss additional involved nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this patient has large breasts and the tumour is 2.5cm in size, there is no need for either \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple mastectomy and axillary node clearance\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical mastectomy and axillary node clearance.\u003C/strong\u003E If the cancer was much larger it may require a \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple mastectomy\u003C/strong\u003E. In the past, if the tumour had locally advanced into adjacent structures (e.g. muscles of the chest wall) a more aggressive surgical approach was used - a \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical mastectomy\u003C/strong\u003E. It is extremely uncommon nowadays to perform a radical mastectomy given the significant deformity that results. If there is evidence of chest wall invasion, most patients would now receive systemic therapy prior to surgery in order to facilitate a simple mastectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple mastectomy and axillary node sampling\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0combines two\u00a0inappropriate approaches - mastectomy is unnecessarily extensive for this tumour size, while sampling is insufficient given the positive sentinel nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The type of resection for a breast tumour will depend on the size of the tumour and any axillary node involvement."],"references":["Lyman GH, Somerfield MR, Giuliano AE. Sentinel lymph node biopsy for patients with early-stage breast cancer: 2016 American Society of Clinical Oncology Clinical Practice Guideline update summary. Journal of Oncology Practice. 2017;13(3):196\u201398. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27937089/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47998"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"736"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47998"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T22:59:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T23:00:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"736"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62551"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"ht